{{noref|date=May 2014}}
[[File:Ioannis (Gennaios) Kolokotronis.JPG|thumb|100px|Ioannis (Gennaios) Kolokotronis]]
'''Ioannis Kolokotronis''' ({{lang-el|Ιωάνης Κολοκοτρώνης}}; 1805–1868{{Greece Old Style dating}}), or '''Gennaios Kolokotronis''' ({{lang-el|Γενναίος Κολοκοτρώνης}}) as the other were calling him was a Greek warrior of the [[Greek War of Independence]], general and the 14th Prime Minister of Greece. He was born at [[Trikolonoi|Stemnitsa]], [[Arcadia]], but he grew up at [[Zakynthos]].
He was a son of [[Theodoros Kolokotronis]] and his mother was Aikaterini Karousou ({{lang-el|Αικατερίνη Καρούσου}}).
He acquired the nickname "Gennaios" (meaning "brave") during the Greek War of Independence in which he fought valiantly despite his youth. 
He took part at the [[Siege of Tripolitsa]], together with his father.

During the [[Greek civil wars of 1824–1825|civil wars]] he sided with his father.

Kolokotronis served as the [[aide de camp]] of [[Otto of Greece|King Otto]] with the rank of [[Major General]], and was appointed by Otto as his last [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]] at 1862. He died on May 23, 1868.

He married the sister of [[Kitsos Tzavelas]], [[Photini Tzavela]] and together they had 2 sons and 5 daughters.

