'''William John Price''' (4 December 1903 – 22 June 1987) was an English professional [[Association football|footballer]], who was born in [[India]]. An [[Midfielder|inside left]], he played for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]], and [[England national amateur football team|England amateurs]]. His most significant spell was with Fulham from 1929 to 1937, who he helped to win the [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] title in 1931–32.
== Club career == Price played for the [[Coldstream Guards]] and the [[10th Royal Hussars]]. He began his professional career at [[Isthmian League]] side Woking Town and joined [[Football League Third Division South|Third Division South]] side [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] in 1928, making his first professional appearance.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title = Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920–2006|last = Haynes|first = Graham|publisher = Yore Publications|year = 2006|isbn = 978-0-9552949-1-4|location =Harefield |pages =128|first2 = Frank|last2 = Coumbe}}</ref> He played for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] between 1928 and 1937, making 204 appearances in all competitions for the club and scoring 53 goals. The "Cottagers" won promotion out of the Third Division South in [[1931–32 Football League|1931–32]], and remained in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] until [[World War II]].
He joined [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] in May 1937.<ref name="kent">{{cite book|last=Kent|first=Jeff|title=Port Vale Personalities|publisher=Witan Books|page=239|year=1996|isbn=0-9529152-0-0|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Port-Vale-Personalities-Jeff-Kent/dp/0952915200}}</ref> He scored two goals in 13 [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]] games in the [[1937–38 Port Vale F.C. season|1937–38]] season, but had his contract at [[The Old Recreation Ground]] cancelled by mutual consent in November 1937 as he wished to travel south to work as a coach.<ref name="kent" /> Price became a coach at [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] upon leaving Port Vale.<ref name="kent" /> He later moved on to become the coach of [[Hillingdon Borough F.C.|Yiewsley]], before his appointment as assistant secretary of Fulham.<ref name="kent" />
== International career == While with Woking, Price won three [[England national amateur football team|England Amateur]] international caps.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslAm.html|title=England Matches – The Amateurs 1906–1939|website=www.englandfootballonline.com|accessdate=2016-10-26}}</ref> In 1929, he was invited to a trial with the [[England national football team|full England side]] and was included in the [[Football Association XI]] for a tour of South Africa and [[Rhodesia]] the same year.<ref name=":1" /><ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/britishfatours.html FA Tours] '''RSSSF'''</ref>
